issue.body:
This minimal GTKmm application should explain what I'm talking about.
```
#include <cstdlib>
#include <iostream>
#include <gtkmm.h>

namespace test {
  class MainWindow : public Gtk::Window {
  public:
    MainWindow() {
      set_title("Example!");
      set_default_size(400, 400);
    }
  };
}

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
  Gio::Application::Flags flags = Gio::Application::Flags::NONE;
  // this is the important line
  auto app = Gtk::Application::create("io.github.jgcodes2020.testapp");
  return app->make_window_and_run<test::MainWindow>(argc, argv);
}
```

When I create the application, it is given a special identifier called a "window class". This can be used, for example to set special compositor rules.

Minecraft currently defaults to `java`. I don't see a function documented anywhere to set this. On unsupported platforms setting the window class should be ignored.
